WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.800
Hi, I'm Rob Hindman, I'm a professor of statistics at Monash University in Australia.

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:14.960
I'll be at the POSIT conference this year leading a workshop on tidy time series and

00:00:14.960 --> 00:00:20.700
forecasting using R. It's relatively common for organisations to collect huge amounts

00:00:20.700 --> 00:00:25.799
of data over time and then find that their existing time series analysis tools are not

00:00:25.799 --> 00:00:29.959
always suitable to handle the scale, the frequency and the structure of the data that have been

00:00:29.959 --> 00:00:30.959
collected.

00:00:30.959 --> 00:00:35.599
For example, you might collect hourly data, but the regular classes in base R aren't designed

00:00:35.599 --> 00:00:36.599
for that.

00:00:36.599 --> 00:00:41.160
Or you might have a lot of time series, but again base R is really designed for single

00:00:41.160 --> 00:00:44.400
series or small numbers of series.

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:48.759
You might have time series stored in a data frame or a tibble, but then the modelling

00:00:48.759 --> 00:00:52.520
tools aren't set up for time series models.

00:00:52.520 --> 00:00:55.799
In this workshop we're going to look at some packages and methods that have been developed

00:00:55.799 --> 00:01:01.759
to handle the analysis of large collections of time series in a tidyverse style.

00:01:01.759 --> 00:01:10.360
It'll be a two-day workshop and on day one we will talk about time series analysis using

00:01:10.360 --> 00:01:11.360
these tools.

00:01:11.360 --> 00:01:15.239
We'll look at the tibble data structure for flexibly managing collections of related time

00:01:15.239 --> 00:01:16.239
series.

00:01:16.239 --> 00:01:21.120
We'll look at how to do data wrangling, data visualisations and exploratory data analysis.

00:01:21.680 --> 00:01:27.040
We'll explore feature-based methods to explore time series data in high dimensions.

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:31.320
A feature-based approach can be used to identify anomalous time series within a collection

00:01:31.320 --> 00:01:36.760
of time series, or to cluster or classify time series.

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:42.400
Primary packages for day one will be the tibble package, lubridate and feasts, along with

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:44.839
the tidyverse of course.

00:01:44.839 --> 00:01:47.040
Day two will be about forecasting.

00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:51.239
We'll look at some classical time series models and how they are automated in the fable

00:01:51.239 --> 00:01:58.360
package and we'll look at ensemble forecasts and hybrid forecasts, and also best practices

00:01:58.360 --> 00:02:01.919
for evaluating forecast accuracy.

00:02:01.919 --> 00:02:06.639
Finally we'll look at forecast reconciliation, allowing millions of time series to be forecast

00:02:06.639 --> 00:02:12.160
in a relatively short time while accounting for constraints on how the series are related

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:13.600
to each other.

00:02:13.600 --> 00:02:15.479
I'm looking forward to it and I hope to see you there.

